'''Miranda de Pencier''' (born August 20, 1968 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] film and television director and producer. She is most noted for her 2011 film ''[[Throat Song]]'', which won the [[Canadian Screen Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Live Action Short Drama|Best Live Action Short Drama]] at the [[1st Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>"Rebelle wins big at Canadian Screen Awards; Grabs 10 statuettes at inaugural event held in Toronto". ''[[Montreal Gazette]]'', March 4, 2013.</ref>
She began her career as an actress, most notably playing Josie Pye in the 1985 ''[[Anne of Green Gables (1985 film)|Anne of Green Gables]]'' series and its sequels.<ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/05/anne-of-green-gables-netflix-cbc "The Sisterhood of Anne of Green Gables Is Ready for Anne’s Next Chapter"]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazines)|Vanity Fair]]'', May 10, 2017.</ref> She also had a recurring role on ''[[Street Legal (Canadian TV series)|Street Legal]]'' in the 1989-90 season as Jennifer Winston, a college student who was dating Chuck Tchobanian,<ref>"It can't be Street Legal to look this good". ''[[Toronto Star]]'', December 26, 1989.</ref> and appeared on stage in Canadian productions of ''[[Les Misérables (musical)|Les Misérables]]'' and ''[[Aspects of Love]]''.<ref>"Aspects transformed by a light touch". ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'', September 6, 1991.</ref>
In the late 1990s she began producing, first in theatre<ref>"Frida Mania: Renowned play opens season at One Yellow Rabbit". ''[[Calgary Herald]]'', September 27, 1997.</ref> before moving into film production. Through her production company, Northwood Entertainment,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/exec/miranda-de-pencier|title=Miranda de Pencier|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> she first produced the 2005 film ''[[Cake (2005 film)|Cake]]''.<ref>"New Canadian romantic comedy, Cake, stars Heather Graham". ''[[Telegraph-Journal]]'', November 30, 2005.</ref> Her subsequent credits as a producer have included the films ''[[Pu-239 (film)|Pu-239]]'', ''[[Adam (2009 film)|Adam]]'' and ''[[Beginners]]'',<ref>"Canuck nominees celebrate in L.A." ''[[Toronto Star]]'', February 24, 2012.</ref> and the television series ''[[Wild Roses (TV series)|Wild Roses]]''<ref>"Wild Roses planted on CBC". ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', January 3, 2009.</ref> and the new 2017 Anne of Green Gables adaptation ''[[Anne (TV series)|Anne]]''.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/anne-series-miranda-de-pencier-1.3405037 "Anne of Green Gables show producer says we can never get too much Anne"]. [[CBC News]] Prince Edward Island, January 15, 2016.</ref>
The short film ''Throat Song'' was her debut as a director.<ref name=premieres>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/iqaluit-made-movie-premieres-at-toronto-film-fest-1.1054643 "Iqaluit-made movie premieres at Toronto film fest"]. [[CBC North]], September 12, 2011.</ref> Her feature debut, ''[[The Grizzlies]]'', debuted at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]] in September 2018. In October, de Pencier won the [[Directors Guild of Canada]] award for Best Direction in a Feature Film for ''The Grizzlies''.<ref>[http://playbackonline.ca/2018/10/22/miranda-de-pencier-kari-skogland-win-dgc-awards/ "Miranda de Pencier, Kari Skogland win DGC Awards"] ''[[Playback (website)|Playback]]'', October 22, 2018.</ref>
==Personal life== She is the daughter of magazine publisher [[Michael de Pencier]], and the sister of documentary filmmaker [[Nicholas de Pencier]].<ref>[https://torontolife.com/city/life/michael-de-pencier-toronto-life/ "The Accidental Mogul"]. ''[[Toronto Life]]'', November 3, 2016.</ref>
