'''On air on sale''' is a policy in the [[music industry]] where [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded music]] is made available for sale at the same time as it is made available for radio broadcast, instead of several weeks later in order to let marketing "buzz" develop, as was former practice. The aim of the policy is to prevent [[copyright infringement]] by making legal [[music download|digital download]]s available as soon as possible. A relatively new development, it is controversial within the music industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1043929|title=UK Government gets behind on air/on sale|publisher=Music Week|date=January 18, 2011|author=Robert Ashton}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/13086221|title=Chipmunk: On Air On Sale 'unfair'|work=[[BBC Newsbeat]]|date=14 April 2011}}</ref>

In 2011, [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]] announced that it will be dropping its on air on sale strategy in the United Kingdom. The strategy was put into practice early this year by both Sony and [[Universal Music|Universal]] in the UK, but has been largely abandoned in favor of "looking at each release on a case-by-case basis," according to a statement from Sony. Singles by Lady Gaga, [[Jessie J]] and [[Chip (rapper)|Chipmunk]] were released as part of this program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perpetua|first1=Matthew|title=Sony Drops 'On Air On Sale' U.K. Strategy|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sony-drops-on-air-on-sale-u-k-strategy-20111012|date=October 12, 2011|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref>

