'''Siega Verde''' ({{IPA-es|ˈsjeɣa ˈβeɾðe}}) is an archaeological site in Serranillo, [[Villar de la Yegua]], [[province of Salamanca]], in [[Castile and León]], [[Spain]]. It was added to the [[Côa Valley Paleolithic Art]] site in the [[World Heritage List]] in 2010.

The site consists of a series of [[rock art|rock carving]]s, discovered in 1988 by professors Manuel Santoja, during an inventory campaign of archaeological sites in the valley of the [[Águeda River (Douro)|Águeda river]]. Subjects include equids, aurochs, deer and goats, among the most common ones, as well as bison, reindeer and the [[woolly rhinoceros]], which were not yet extinct at the time. 

The engravings date to the [[Gravettian]] culture of the [[Upper Palaeolithic]] (circa 20,000 years ago). There are also more recent, anthropomorphic representations, dating to the [[Magdalenian]] age (c. 9,000 years ago). There is a total of 91 panels, spanning some 1 kilometers of rock.

